# Clip-to-Image Action Recognition

A lightweight action-recognition pipeline that collapses each video clip into a **single image** and classifies it with a frozen **VGG16** backbone. Instead of running heavy end-to-end video models, every clip is reduced to one 224×224×3 representation, making preprocessing and inference cheap while keeping accuracy competitive.

The repository compares four clip-to-image representations under an identical training protocol (same frozen-VGG16 head, same stratified 5-fold cross validation) for a fair, apples-to-apples evaluation:

| Method | Representation |
|---|---|
| **Pixel Variance** *(ours)* | Grayscale temporal variance of all frames, replicated to 3 channels |
| **Mean Image** | Grayscale temporal mean of all frames, replicated to 3 channels |
| **Middle Frame** | The true RGB middle frame of the clip |
| **Dynamic Image** | Approximate rank pooling (Bilen et al., TPAMI 2018) |

## Dataset

The pipeline expects a 7-class action dataset organized as one subfolder per class, each containing video clips:

```
data/
├── Move/
├── Pick/
├── Place/
├── Reach/
├── Retract/
├── Tilt/
└── Wipe/
```

Supported video formats: `.mp4`, `.avi`, `.mov`, `.mkv`. Every video is used exactly once — **no augmentation, no class balancing, no synthetic copies.** Each class must contain at least `N_FOLDS` (default 5) videos for stratified cross validation to work.

The full **Video2SubAct Dataset** is not publicly downloadable and is available for non-commercial research use only, on request. See [Dataset Access](#dataset-access) below.

