## Repository structure

```
.
├── src/
│   ├── DHI_VGG16.py                  # Full pipeline incl. Dynamic Image + SOTA comparison (Table II)
│   ├── mean_middle_pixelVariance.py  # Core 3 methods: Pixel Variance, Mean Image, Middle Frame
│   └── backbone_comparison_pvi.py    # Backbone comparison (ResNet-50 / EfficientNet-B0 / MobileNetV3) on pre-made PVI images
├── assets/                           # Pipeline diagrams used in this README
├── Sample/                           # One example clip per class, under each method
│   ├── PixelVariance/
│   ├── MeanImage/
│   ├── MiddleFrame/
│   └── DHI_VGG16/
├── Dataset/                          # Dataset license / access agreement
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
└── LICENSE
```

The repository contains two kinds of experiments:

**1. Representation comparison (video input).** `mean_middle_pixelVariance.py` and `DHI_VGG16.py` decode raw videos and compare different clip-to-image representations on the same frozen-VGG16 head. `mean_middle_pixelVariance.py` runs the three core representations (Pixel Variance, Mean Image, Middle Frame); `DHI_VGG16.py` additionally implements the Dynamic Image baseline and produces a lightweight-vs-heavy video-model comparison table.

![Video clip-to-image VGG16 pipeline](assets/video_clip_to_image_vgg16_pipeline.png)

**2. Backbone comparison (pre-made PVI input).** `backbone_comparison_pvi.py` skips video decoding entirely and loads the Pixel Variance Images (PVI) you have already generated and saved as PNGs. It holds the input and folds fixed while swapping the backbone — ResNet-50, EfficientNet-B0, and MobileNetV3 — each ImageNet-pretrained and **partially fine-tuned** (only the top conv block is unfrozen). This isolates the effect of the backbone for an apples-to-apples comparison on identical inputs. It reports Top-1 accuracy, precision, recall, and macro F1-score per fold.

![PVI backbone comparison pipeline](assets/pvi_backbone_comparison_pipeline.png)

## Installation

```bash
git clone https://github.com/dohaerix/pixel-variance-action-recognition.git
cd pixel-variance-action-recognition
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

A GPU is recommended (training runs many folds for many epochs), but the scripts run on CPU as well.

## Usage

1. Open the script you want to run and edit the **CONFIGURATION** block near the top:

   ```python
   DATA_DIR   = "/path/to/data"      # root folder, one subfolder per class
   OUTPUT_DIR = "/path/to/results"   # everything is written here
   METHODS_TO_RUN = [...]            # which representations to run
   ```

2. Run:

   ```bash
   python src/mean_middle_pixelVariance.py
   # or, for the full pipeline with Dynamic Image:
   python src/DHI_VGG16.py
   # or, to compare backbones on pre-made PVI images:
   python src/backbone_comparison_pvi.py
   ```

For `backbone_comparison_pvi.py`, `DATA_DIR` must point to a folder of pre-generated **Pixel Variance Image (PVI) PNGs**, laid out one subfolder per class (`Move/*.png`, `Pick/*.png`, …) — no video decoding happens in this script. Its backbones are selected via `MODELS_TO_RUN`, and the fraction of the network that is unfrozen for fine-tuning is controlled by `FT_UNFREEZE_LAYERS` (default 20).

Key hyperparameters (also in the CONFIGURATION block):

| Parameter | Default | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `N_FOLDS` | 5 | Stratified cross-validation folds |
| `TARGET_SIZE` | (224, 224) | VGG16 input size |
| `EPOCHS` | 1500 | Training epochs per fold |
| `BATCH_SIZE` | 12 | Mini-batch size |
| `LR` | 1e-4 | Learning rate |
| `NUM_CLASSES` | 7 | Number of action classes |
| `RANDOM_SEED` | 42 | Reproducibility seed |

### Resume support

All scripts are **resume-safe**. If a run is interrupted (crash, kill, power loss), simply re-run the same command — any fold whose model file and metrics row already exist on disk is skipped, and execution continues from where it stopped. This holds across methods/backbones, not just within one.

## Outputs

Everything is written under `OUTPUT_DIR`. For each method:

```
<OUTPUT_DIR>/
├── PixelVariance/
│   ├── models/                     # trained VGG16 head per fold (.h5)
│   ├── plots/                      # accuracy, loss, confusion matrix, 3D t-SNE
│   ├── data/                       # exact numerical data behind every plot (CSV)
│   ├── representation_images/      # the actual 224×224×3 image fed to VGG16, per clip
│   ├── representation_image_manifest.csv
│   ├── metrics_per_fold.csv
│   └── per_fold_table_rows.csv
├── MeanImage/        (same structure)
├── MiddleFrame/      (same structure)
├── comparison_table_raw.csv        # every per-fold value, all methods stacked
├── Table_I_ablation_study.csv      # formatted mean ± std (IEEE Table I style)
├── Table_I_per_fold_raw.csv
└── plot_manifest.csv               # index of every plot PNG + its paired CSV
```

`DHI_VGG16.py` additionally writes `Table_II_sota_comparison.csv` and `Table_II_per_fold_raw.csv`, comparing the lightweight clip-to-image methods against heavy end-to-end video models (ViViT, VideoMAE). Those video-model numbers are manual placeholders — fill in the `SOTA_VIDEO_RESULTS` dictionary at the top of the script with your own measurements and re-run (training is skipped via the resume logic).

`backbone_comparison_pvi.py` writes `Table_main_results.csv` (mean ± std per backbone) and `Table_main_per_fold_raw.csv` instead of the Table I/II files.

## Metrics

Each fold reports Top-1 accuracy, macro F1-score (and precision/recall for the backbone comparison), per-clip preprocessing time (ms), per-clip inference latency (ms), and throughput (FPS). Every plot is mirrored by a CSV containing the exact values behind it, so all figures are fully reproducible from disk.

## Dataset Access

The **Video2SubAct Dataset** is not publicly available and cannot be downloaded directly. Researchers wishing to use it must first submit a written request to the corresponding author; access is granted at the authors' discretion under a signed non-commercial research-use agreement. See [`Dataset/LICENSE_AGREEMENT_Video2SubAct_Dataset.pdf`](Dataset/LICENSE_AGREEMENT_Video2SubAct_Dataset.pdf) for the full terms.

Requests for access should be sent to the corresponding author: **Dharmendra Sharma**, Indian Institute of Technology Mandi, Himachal Pradesh, India — `d22194@students.iitmandi.ac.in`.

## Reference

The Dynamic Image baseline follows Bilen et al., *"Action Recognition with Dynamic Image Networks"*, IEEE TPAMI, 2018.

